defaultRegulatory Approaches around UKdefaultThe different regulatory regimes for buildings across the UK are set out in the following legislation: 
default&#xa0;
defaultSAP Treatment of Thermal MassdefaultThermal mass is incorporated into SAP via a ‘thermal mass parameter’, which is the summation of the heat capacity of the surfaces in contact with th
defaulte internal air divided by the total floor area.
defaultIt influences the result in two ways:
defaultFirst, greater mass leads to better utilisation of solar gains, particularly when received outside heating periods, since the walls and other surfaces can store heat.
defaultSec
defaultondly, it also means that the internal temperature drops less rapidly when the heating is off. 
defaultThese effects act in opposite directions.  The first leads to a reduction in the energy demand to be supplied by the heating system as thermal mass increased, w
defaulthile the second leads to an increase because of higher internal temperature averaged over 24 hours and thus the potential for greater heat loss depending on the insulation levels. 
defaultFor dwellings with poor or moderate insulation levels, the latter has the g
defaultreater effect, so that higher mass tends to give a higher space heating energy requirement. For high insulation levels, particularly if coupled with passive solar design, the former can have the greater effect, with higher mass giving a lower energy requir
defaultement.
defaultWork of the Heat Network Delivery UnitdefaultDuring the first round of bids for the Heat Networks Delivery Unit’s grant support programmes, a total of 131 requests for application forms were received from 84 Local Authorities. This led to 31 Local Authori
defaultties submitting completing applications relating to 53 separate projects. 
defaultThese projects have been assessed by the department against value for money and other published criteria 
defaultand the
default Secretary of State is expected to make a formal announcement regardi
defaultng payment of the grants in January 2014.
defaultThe second round of the grant support programme was opened on 27
defaultth
default November
default, with
default a deadline for applications of  31
defaultst
default January. We are happy to keep the Committee updated as to the progress being made.
defaultVentilationdefault 
defaultThe Green Deal incorporates robust procedures to ensure that work is done by competent installers and in accordance with all relevant requirements of the Building Regulations including Part F Means of ventilation and Part J Combustion appliances.
defaultFor exis
defaultting properties, the Green Deal Code of Practice states that where a package of improvements is proposed to be installed under a Green Deal Plan, it is the responsibility of the Green Deal Provider to ensure that the products installed are properly integra
defaultted with each other and with any previously installed energy efficiency measures in order to minimise the risk of damage to the building fabric as a consequence of inadequate ventilation or inadequate air tightness, particularly where the installed measure
defaults include internal or external solid wall insulation systems, cavity wall insulation or replacement or secondary glazing.  
defaultFor new build, Part F of Building Regulations requires an appropriate ventilation strategy, taking into account the requirements for
default conservation of fuel and energy (and thus the need for air tightness) set out in Part L of Building Regulations. Part L of Building Regulations in turn also takes account of the energy impact of any mechanical or natural ventilation system required under 
defaultPart F.
default&#xa0;
defaultHeat Pump Bill SavingsdefaultThrough their heat pump field trial, EST has provided the main source of evidence on in-situ performance of heat pumps in the UK.
default&#xa0;
default Phase 1 of the field trial measured 83 systems mainly installed in 2008.
default&#xa0;
default DECC analysed these
default results in detail and published a report, which is available on our website:
defaulthttps://www.gov.uk/government/publication
defaults/analysis-from-the-first-phase-of-the-energy-saving-trust-s-heat-pump-field-trial
defaultThese results were disappointing but they have been used constructively by DECC and industry to develop improved heat pump installation standards, which have been in plac
defaulte since April 2012.
defaultEST’s field trial continued for a second phase with a reduced sample size after interventions had taken place.
default&#xa0;
default DECC’s detailed analysis of these results are available on 
defaultthe same webpage.
default&#xa0;
default They generally show significant improvements w
defaulthere interventions have been made.
defaultMore recently, DECC have been running a new metering programme in the Renewable Heat Premium Payment.
default&#xa0;
default The sample size of this field trial is significantly larger than EST’s (approximately 700 systems) but the data collec
defaulttion exercise will not conclude until October 2014.
defaultIt is not straightforward to match up metered sites with their previous heating fuel, make assumptions about the metered person’s previous system’s efficiency, heating energy consumption and fuel prices a
defaultnd produce an estimate of bill savings.
default&#xa0;
default However, by making reasonable assumptions, we should be able to present our new data in a way that estimates the proportion of installations that reduced the occupants’ heating bills.
defaultWe intend to publish a short re
defaultport in January showing examples of the data we are collecting in the RHPP metering programme.
default&#xa0;
default In that report we can also include an assessment of the Seasonal Performance Factors required to generate fuel bill savings in different scenarios under particu
defaultlar assumptions.
defaultGas Network Strategy GroupdefaultThe Department continues to engage with stakeholders. At the moment we are unsure what value a formal Gas Network Strategy Group would add to the conversations and engagement already taking place. However we will
default continue to consider the option and have no objection to a 
defaultgroup being formed if it would add significant value to the process.
defaultWhole defaultSdefaultystems defaultAdefaultpproach and defaultIdefaultntegration across defaultGdefaultovernmentdefault  
defaultDECC’s Whole Energy System work is an overarching programme that int
defaultegrates two projects considering electricity system topics and multi-vector challenges (e.g. future of the gas grid, role of hydrogen).
default&#xa0;
default The work is focused on delivering answers to key policy questions from a position that takes in the entire energy syste
defaultm under a number of scenarios out to 2050. The team is working with key external centres of energy system expertise, including UCL’s Energy Institute, the Energy Technology Institute and National Grid in order to understand what system thinking and modelli
defaultng is already being undertaken. 
default&#xa0;
defaultEach workstream takes a structured approach to scope potential issues and current practice before defining what capabilities will be required to shape the future decarbonised energy system.
default&#xa0;
default By verifying and building on exi
defaultsting system modelling capabilities, it will help DECC deliver a fit for purpose energy system at the lowest cost to tax payers.
defaultThe programme will work with a Whole Systems Modelling Expert Panel containing advisers from a range of other Government depart
defaultments as well as industry and academia. In this way, we plan to capture insights from all perspectives on the energy system.
